    <a title="Melody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3884378-melody"><img alt="Melody" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493753494p2/3884378.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1308996711?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melody" href="/user/show/3884378-melody">Melody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3884378-melody?shelf=2015">2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1308996711" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14126610503865785598">Wow...this was just exactly my sort of book and I&apos;m so smashed full of love for it that I&apos;m having a hard time talking about it coherently. All the characters are so so real, flawed but lovable (or hate-able) and presented in just the way that life presents you with people. It explores some of those deep questions of life that I often feel alone in pondering, but I&apos;ve found a friend in this book. I loved the American Irish culture, the family dynamics, the era, and the never-ending struggle betw</span>
  <span id="freeText14126610503865785598" style="display:none">Wow...this was just exactly my sort of book and I'm so smashed full of love for it that I'm having a hard time talking about it coherently. All the characters are so so real, flawed but lovable (or hate-able) and presented in just the way that life presents you with people. It explores some of those deep questions of life that I often feel alone in pondering, but I've found a friend in this book. I loved the American Irish culture, the family dynamics, the era, and the never-ending struggle between what we want and what is good for us. If ever you find yourself in the mood for some deep thought or a contemplative character study, this just might be the ticket.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14126610503865785598" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

