    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_917363999" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/917363999" />
    <a title="Tsung" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung"><img alt="Tsung" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298808605p2/4992851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/917363999?book_show_action=true">Apr 22, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tsung" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tsung" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung">Tsung</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer917363999" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17367827703990155721">Lovely book. More of a psychosocial study than a plot driven story. I would not usually start, let alone finish such a book, but the expression and descriptions strike a chord within. This is a book which shines, not for clever plots or elegant writing, but it resonates. There were many feelings and situations that I could personally identify with. The events which mark out the story at points are few and far between. As such, the plot moves at a leisurely pace. More importantly is the impact on</span>
  <span id="freeText17367827703990155721" style="display:none">Lovely book. More of a psychosocial study than a plot driven story. I would not usually start, let alone finish such a book, but the expression and descriptions strike a chord within. This is a book which shines, not for clever plots or elegant writing, but it resonates. There were many feelings and situations that I could personally identify with. The events which mark out the story at points are few and far between. As such, the plot moves at a leisurely pace. More importantly is the impact on the different characters. While each character finds his or her own station in life, each also has a secret, a part of their lives which remains unfulfilled, unsatisfied. The story revolves around the Carmody family, particularly its domineering patriarch Charlie. We encounter them through the eyes of Father Hugh Kennedy. He stands by as an observer, always watching, listening and analyzing as each one opens themselves up to him. He, himself, is battling his own private demons, having lost his stature and parish through the ills of alcoholism, he struggles to find his own niche. I could not understand what the deal was with Helen until the end when she revealed her past feelings for Hugh. After years of marriage and already becoming a grandmother, it is curious why she should now seek some sort of security in Hugh's affirmation of reciprocal feelings for her. The plot twist was clever, ironic and spiced up the story as it reached the end. A good read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17367827703990155721" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


