    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2824086730" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2824086730" />
    <a title="A Enwright" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3882746-a-enwright"><img alt="A Enwright" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2824086730?book_show_action=true">May 17, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="A Enwright" class="user" itemprop="url" name="A Enwright" href="/user/show/3882746-a-enwright">A Enwright</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2824086730&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2824086730" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14792636624480059300">I really enjoyed this book. There are many really wonderful reviews about the book on Goodreads here. I am not really sure I can add anything new. As others have said, it&apos;s heart-achingly beautiful and although not much happens externally, the narrator is Father Hugh Kennedy, and the story basically is about how he changes. It&apos;s a kind of psychological unfolding. <br/><br/>In the early 60&apos;s it seems to me (and I&apos;m generalizing) there was this movement of getting down to the psychological raw nub of things</span>
  <span id="freeText14792636624480059300" style="display:none">I really enjoyed this book. There are many really wonderful reviews about the book on Goodreads here. I am not really sure I can add anything new. As others have said, it's heart-achingly beautiful and although not much happens externally, the narrator is Father Hugh Kennedy, and the story basically is about how he changes. It's a kind of psychological unfolding. <br /><br />In the early 60's it seems to me (and I'm generalizing) there was this movement of getting down to the psychological raw nub of things. If you think of Edward Albee's plays, Who's Afraid of Virginia Wolfe? or The Zoo Story, the characters reveal themselves through their dialogue, but there is no resolution. They basically destroy themselves and each other in the process of self-revelation. It's a tearing down without a building up. Here that possibility comes up (in Father Hugh's last dialogue with Father John), but Father Hugh, through the grace of God, manages to transcend it. It's the story of vocation, of one priest's journey and healing. And it ends on a note of joy, even though externally everything is the same. <br /><br />It's also the story of an unhappy Irish Catholic family with a narcissistic parent, who all look fine from the outside. They have money, they're able to take care of their kids, etc. But the father, Charlie, basically uses everyone in the family (and outside the family) to do his bidding. His manipulation of others comes from a selfish protectiveness. He does not trust other people and only feels comfortable in a world where he is totally in charge of everyone and everything. In 1961, people weren't talking about narcissistic parents. <br /><br />To me, because Father Hugh saw right through Charlie Carmody, other than having an attachment to the family, it was unclear to me why he was willing to put up with Charlie's shenanigans. But then again, this is fiction. The unhappy family part made me wonder how this novel would compare to another early 20th century novel about an unhappy Catholic family called Brideshead Revisited. That novel too was told from the perspective of an outsider to the family. <br /><br />Unlike other books I have read about priests written in the first half of the 20th century (See Keys of the Kingdom by Cronin), the priest here is humble, self-effacing, acutely realistic, and kind. The priest in Keys of the Kingdom was almost a kind of superhero, more plastic; every situation that could have happened to him, happened to him, and he came through with flying colors just by the skin of his teeth. Here, less happens, the priest is assigned to three parishes, and a recovery center, but more happens inside Father Hugh's soul than anything that happens externally in Keys of the Kingdom. <br /><br />Some of the dialogue in the book between PJ, Bucky, and Charlie is hysterical. It's a bit of a comic caricature... but the banter is used to hide because to reveal oneself to another person in any significant way was considered shameful. You never tell your secrets to anyone and so you focus on the trivia. And if you get caught because you slip up, you try to rewrite the dialogue that took place by saying, I was out of my mind. And you repeat this about 25 times to your hearer. Father Hugh's dialogues with Father Dankowski are also really well-done. The portrayal of the young curate as an eager young pup is at first annoying, and then appealing because you see his goodness and his willingness to both serve and think the best of people, even if those people have hurt you or your family. <br /><br />One of the overriding themes in the book is appearance versus reality. Who is the successful priest, Father John or Father Hugh? How is success measured? Whose family is the "successful" family, the Carmody's, Father Hugh's father, or the Dankowski family? Whose family really is the model family and does the model depend on money? I think maybe in an unconscious way, it was an invitation of the author to re-look at the rising materialism of post-World War II America. Maybe I am reading too much into it. <br /><br />Some of the situations in the book I do not think would happen today given the Church's recent history. And this is a good thing. The ethnicity of that 1950s world is all but gone. But if you look at it as a glimpse into the heart of one particular priest with one particular history living at one particular time, rather than at the priesthood as a whole per se, you will find that the feelings expressed are timeless and universal. This review is just a long-winded way of saying that I really, really liked this book, and highly recommend it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14792636624480059300" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


