        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2946597150" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5951748211825666185">I really enjoyed this book. It is told from the viewpoint of a priest named Hugh who went through a period of time as an alcoholic. He has recovered from his alcoholism and is thrown back into the lives of the Carmodys. Charlie Carmody is a cranky old man who was a friend of Hugh&apos;s father. Hugh grew up with and was good friends with two of Charlie&apos;s children, Helen and John (also a priest). Through the Carmodys, Hugh reflects on his life and in particular what his alcoholism has taught him. &quot;The</span>
  <span id="freeText5951748211825666185" style="display:none">I really enjoyed this book. It is told from the viewpoint of a priest named Hugh who went through a period of time as an alcoholic. He has recovered from his alcoholism and is thrown back into the lives of the Carmodys. Charlie Carmody is a cranky old man who was a friend of Hugh's father. Hugh grew up with and was good friends with two of Charlie's children, Helen and John (also a priest). Through the Carmodys, Hugh reflects on his life and in particular what his alcoholism has taught him. "The Edge of Sadness" refers to the Carmodys and Hugh. In the end it appears that the Carmodys remain on the edge of sadness while Hugh has come out of it and is content with his life. The novel sheds some interesting light on the Catholic church. There seem to be some superficial things going on and yet also some true faith. This novel was a good choice and I highly recommend it.</span>
