<div id="review_2520587007" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2520587007" />
    <a title="Tim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75270105-tim"><img alt="Tim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1552249586p2/75270105.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2520587007?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tim" href="/user/show/75270105-tim">Tim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/75270105-tim?shelf=pulitzer-prize-winners-fiction">pulitzer-prize-winners-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2520587007" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14626417831091407757">Edwin O&apos;Connor&apos;s book, The Edge of Sadness won the Pulitzer prize in 1962. The story is about a man of the clergy, Hugh Kennedy, and his journey to find his place in the church and how relationships when he was a boy affect his journey. I liked the writing style of the author in that he provides a very introspective view of the main characters. I give this book 4 stars.</span>
  <span id="freeText14626417831091407757" style="display:none">Edwin O'Connor's book, The Edge of Sadness won the Pulitzer prize in 1962. The story is about a man of the clergy, Hugh Kennedy, and his journey to find his place in the church and how relationships when he was a boy affect his journey. I liked the writing style of the author in that he provides a very introspective view of the main characters. I give this book 4 stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14626417831091407757" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


